\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ScarcityClarification"

\end_inset

A note on the notion of scarcity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scarcity can be a confusing term since it encompasses both a so-called physical
 scarcity (unavailability) and the perceived scarcity (what we feel as scarce).
 We'll assume that all felt scarcities are physically scarce (otherwise
 consumers would acquire the item that is meant to be scarce).
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subset S$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 denotes the felt scarcities and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 the direct physical scarcities.
 Unfortunately, the perceptions of quality of life are entities that cannot
 be measured easily but still may qualify as felt scarcities.
 This makes the claims on scarcity as a driver of demand particularly difficult.
 Wherever used in the study, the term scarcity implies the notion of perceived
 scarcity (
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

) which may be affected by artificial unavailability or barriers (i.e.
 such barriers may extend 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 by including entities available only through status competitions, advertising
 or other social-psychological communication).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Further, the nature of item matters for perceived scarcity since the direction
 of the effect of popularity on perceived scarcity can reverse depending
 on the demand of the item (visual or status-related).
 If everybody has a certain item, then consumers may not consider it so
 important to acquire the item (since everyone else already has it) whereas
 for other types of item, consumers may rush to the item solely because
 there is a trend amongst everybody else to acquire.
 These are the snob and bandwagon types of item considered in the literature
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

.
 Researchers have used an extended social-means model to measure these in
 experiments
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gierl_scarcity"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

