\begin_layout Subsection
Status and Political Economy in sub-Saharan Africa
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Both Fred Hirsch and Joseph Schumpeter - whose work frequently works are
 frequently referred to in the study - had viewed industrial revolution
 as a legacy of liberal capitalism - a race amongst the middle classes to
 achieve the higher social positions once held by the feudal elite
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits,SchumpeterCapitalism"

\end_inset

.
 Developments of the last century in Africa and Asia bear similarity to
 this phenomenon where a new working class has clashed with feudal and colonial
 systems of the century before.
 The growing status competitions amongst the nascent working classes have
 been a subject of sociological study in the late 20th century.
 In India of the 1950s, for example, this competition was termed as Sanskritizat
ion when erstwhile lower classes emulated higher social classes with newly
 acquired economic freedoms
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The status competitions as well as the collective defense of non-positional
 goods
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
Both Hirsch and Frank have argued for policy control of status competitions
 for positional goods.
 Hirsch summarizes the problems of controlling distribution as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

adding-up problem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 [sic] - where a group of individuals fail to pursue a common goal (e.g.
 defence of public goods or safety) as it isn't broken down into individual
 responsibilities (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

when everyone stands on tiptoes, no one sees better
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in the developing world has hardly followed the route of Georgian England.
 The industrial class in the countries is relatively poor in absolute terms
 and the problems of extreme poverty have remained largely unresolved in
 large swathes of Asia and Africa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
It would be inaccurate though to draw wide-ranging conclusions based on
 economic poverty.
 The administrative successes and stabilities of post-colonial governments
 are varied and have depended on the extent of agrarian empires that had
 existed before.
 The extractive administrative frameworks of Ottoman or Moghul empires,
 for example, could be adapted well by European colonists in Asian countries
 when compared to the administrative units (much as the political boundaries
 themselves) created in sub-Saharan Africa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Despite regional differences, the political landscape of Asian and African
 economies is dominated by effects of decolonization - a process that encompasse
s the loosely similar post-war political voices in Asia and Africa aspiring
 to establish nation-states.
 While centralization was attempted for decades in both Asia and Africa
 - often curtailing local-level status competitions and individual freedoms
 alike - their limited reach and success has prevented the freedom of status
 competitions.
 It is difficult to observe whether countries undergoing military conflict
 have higher measures of status competitions but there is little doubt that
 government-driven resettlements and urban movements of the 20th century
 can have an impact on identities and the pace of industrialisation (both
 of which affect status-related consumption).
 The state of urban development that most developing countries are in, the
 status competitions that may have otherwise been limited to tribal or local
 levels can now find expressions in urban settings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LaherAfricaIndigenous"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Factors influencing status consumption or signaling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Competitions for Social mobility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As far as market principles can work, status and mobility have a key role
 to play in economic development.
 The core of Adam Smith's arguments is that economic progress can be achieved
 by letting an exchange between the rich and poor thrive.
 In a world where Adam Smith lived, to quote from Wicksteed, trinkets could
 be turned into bread
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WicksteedCommonSense"

\end_inset

.
 From a certain point of view, more spending on a conspicuous item would
 benefit the society as a whole - since the money obtained from the rich
 on the item could potentially fund employment and other opportunities.
 Electricity would for example be a model item for this purpose in Africa
 - an item whose consumption can drive the expansion of power plants and
 make electricity cheaper.
 From such a perspective, more spending on signaling goods does not appear
 to be a social waste.
 However, not all goods are as desirable as electricity and there may be
 goals more desirable than what the said exchange can provide.
 A perspective offered by Frederich Hirsch was that in the Western world,
 the differences between the rich and poor have already been reduced to
 a level that this exchange (or the workings of the invisible hand) could
 not be made lucrative to the poor any more.
 Under the pressure of its own success, therefore, the exchange now faces
 the price of luxuries having exceeded the opportunity cost to the rest
 of the society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the basic needs for the masses haven't been addressed in the developing
 world, there are reasons to think that an exchange between rich and poor
 can draw the masses out of poverty in Africa.
 There are again limits to achieving this success in the developing countries.
 The essential goods often lack a market in the developing countries and
 since marketable goods often create needs on their own, the development
 of market for conspicuous goods may prevent the status competitions away
 from achieving the goals of social welfare.
 The way societies are structured, anything available to the richer sections
 of the society can easily become a status good and thus the possibility
 of a social waste cannot be ruled out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The limits to welfare can in fact be further worsened by weak institutions.
 The developing countries seem to have followed their own paths to economic
 development while achieving goals of nationalism - and they now face the
 problem of institutions not being strong enough to establish the said exchange
 between the rich and the poor.
 In the new urban settings in Africa, both tribal identities and the hierarchies
 formed through education, money or industrial assets now contribute to
 status competitions.
 While this development can encourage institutions of money and education
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Status differences as such are only going to spur consumption on status
 goods (education should be considered as part of status consumption).
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the status competitions in absence of welfare-centered institutions can
 limit themselves to markets not developed enough to undertake physical
 scarcities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between education, urban developments, income levels and
 tribal identities is difficult to assess without access to the microdata
 on tribal identities and regional migration.
 In absence of such data (as is the case with LSMS used in the study), we
 may consider other proxies that may correlated with social identities (e.g.
 family income levels, language spoken, locality etc.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The LSMS data is available to enumeration-area levels in the crowded regions
 (which are over-represented in the samples).
\end_layout

