\begin_layout Subsubsection
Scarcity or Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In simple terms, a signaling product indicates the buyer's status to the
 immediate surroundings.
 Status being a sociological phenomenon, it becomes non-trivial to classify
 a good as a signaling good.
 If for example, only the rich could afford electricity in a society, electricit
y may not appear as a signaling product for most of the population.
 From the point of view of consumption, a good being used by a smaller and
 richer part of the population has less significance than a good used by
 the majority of the population.
 This observation is relevant in a regression with consumption on an item
 as the dependent variable.
 For a selection approach to represent the zero consumption on an item,
 we consider the supply of an item.
 This is based on the observation that when an item is in limited supply,
 only those consumers with higher purchasing power (or those who must pass
 some other barrier) would have access to it.
 For example, if electricity is not available throughout the country, then
 only those with higher income or with residence in certain areas (where
 there is electricity) can have their signaling needs fulfilled with the
 item.
 In other words, when expenditure on the item is limited to the richer sections
 of society, then the item is a status good merely through being a statement
 of wealth
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The difference between concepts of physical and social scarcity described
 by Hirsch
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset

 is discarded in this approach.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Flocking towards the item
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The price of the item in the market or other barriers for distribution of
 the desired item matters is not all that determines a status good.
 A status good needs to be understood in relation to other commodities.
 As a preliminary analysis, we rely on time-series change of the budget
 share (analysis of elasticities) to see how sensitive the budget share
 of an item is to time, income and supply.
 The equilibrium consumption values can shift when a higher supply is provided
 (more electrical power plants or cheaper alternative energy would reduce
 the budget share on electricity).
 If the budget share of electricity is high or increases then we can consider
 that people may be flocking to the commodity (income elasticity may also
 partially captures this).
 The causes for this flocking (whether the consumers feel they're in a better
 status) are beyond the scope of a budget survey - but whether an increased
 supply would increase the consumption significantly indicates the consumption
 pressure to the commodity
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This measure of flocking is termed as bandwagon effect in the study.
\end_layout

\end_inset

