\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The demand functions ( 
\begin_inset Formula $q=g(x)$
\end_inset

 ) would be well behaved if once an item 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is 
\shape italic
revealed
\shape default
 as preferred to item 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 would be preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 even if the consumer was compensated more.
 This was originally proposed by Samuelson and then extended to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 items by Houthakker.
 The revealed preference theory leads to the Slutsky equations (that give
 us the matrix of substitution effects) - which can be summarised as the
 negative-semi-definiteness of the substitution matrix and the symmetry
 of cross-substitution effects 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In practice these properties may not be exactly true for the data.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The well-known AIDS model - a particular version of the Rotterdam model
 - is an example of such a model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of conspicuous consumption, the preferences are expected
 to be comparable and transitive.
 The axiom of revealed preference is thus expected to hold i.e.
 when an item is revealed preferred to another item - then more income would
 continue to maintain that item preferred.
 However, assuming any further restrictions on the utility curves requires
 a theoretical justification as well as the empirical tests associated with
 assumption of the shape of the utility curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A commonly used restriction is that of separability.
 A convenient way to think of separability (and the necessary and sufficient
 conditions for it
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The necessary and sufficient condition for separability is the marginal
 rate of substitution between any two variables in the same group being
 independent of a variable in any other group.
\end_layout

\end_inset

) is to view separability as a hierarchy of needs - i.e.
 a utility tree - where needs are split into multiple groups - each of which
 further expands as sub-groups that eventually enlist individual items.
 The items in each group can be rearranged within the group by the consumer
 without affecting the items in other groups (except through the effect
 of the expenditure associated with the item on the total income).
 An aggregation of this tree is equivalent to the combination of sub-utility
 functions that each of the branch in the tree corresponds to.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal utility problem then amounts to optimising sub-utility functions
 i.e.
 the utility in each group and then in the aggregation of groups.
 For every group 
\begin_inset Formula $r\epsilon G$
\end_inset

, the consumer would thus optimise 
\begin_inset Formula $c(u_{r},p_{r})=min[x=\sum q_{i}p_{i,r}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{r}(x,p_{r})=u_{r}]$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{r}$
\end_inset

 in these problems would be chosen subject to the combined utility function
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{G}$
\end_inset

 such that the consumer optimises:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
C(u,p)=min[x=\sum p_{G}q_{G}\ for\ u_{G}(x,p)=u\label{eq:broad_group_allocation}
\end{multline}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem can be solved if the prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{g\epsilon G}$
\end_inset

