\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Development of Inequalities and of status differences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
In recent decades, the urban settlements in Africa have seen massive overpopulat
ion and development of the services sector.
 The differences in urban-rural lifestyles have increased.
 The scarcity of services and of industrial goods (which would be a necessity
 in the Western world) seem evidently sparse in the developing countries
 (a claim that is verified by data on Tanzania).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
A relevant question amidst these developments is whether a consumer prefers
 a larger house over installation of electricity or not.
 As a commodity, electricity is both scarce and visible - as it opens up
 more lifestyle choices.
 The game designed in the Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:GameScarcity"

\end_inset

 aims to test the presence of a preference for electricity (and other scarce
 goods) - but as is, the data suggests significant urban-rural differences
 across regions in Tanzania.
 In a Hirschian sense, a social congestion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset

 is likely to exist for electricity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
A general view on scarcity would allow us to classify the commodities based
 on their scarcity and quantify the urban-rural differences better.
 The game detailed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:GameScarcity"

\end_inset

 may further help measure the impact of such scarcities on consumer preferences.
 It is noted that many of the items are scarce together (carpets and housing-sta
tus, electricity and hobby equipment, etc.) .
 It is through such denial of goods and services that status perceptions
 develop.
 A simple view of observed scarcities can be provided by a directed graph
 of items for classification - where a node is an item and points to other
 nodes/items that it denies (which themselves can be formed with items that
 deny other items and so and so forth).
 For example, electricity can be a node in this graph with connections to
 equipment and electronics but no connection to food items.
 The disconnected nodes in the graph - would be least likely to be affected
 by another unreachable node in the graph.
 The criteria of connections (denials) would be determined by statistical
 significance e.g.
 rice and walnuts appear would not be scarce together if one of them is
 available and affordable by both higher and lower quantiles of permanent
 income of society.
 This would be developed further as the study progresses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing single
Modeling and Measurement - Status vs Visibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Even when the ideas of conspicuous consumption have been revived in works
 of Ireland
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

 or Arrow, Dasgputa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArrowDasgupta"

\end_inset

, the literature has relied on what is considered wasteful - thus modeling
 conspicuous consumption as the difference between social welfare and market
 equilibrium.
 Some studies have focussed on visibility as the mechanism for status-related
 consumption .
 The signaling model provided by Ireland
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

 - where consumers attempt to maximise a combined utility of visible (public)
 and non-visible (private) consumption
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The utility function is modeled as 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(1-a)f(v,w)+af(\hat{v},\hat{w})$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{v},\hat{w}$
\end_inset

 are societies' view of the consumption and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(>0)$
\end_inset

 is a parameter indicating how much visible consumption matters to the consumer.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - is of remarkable simplicity but calibrating it involves a sensitivity-paramet
er of how much visible consumption matters to the consumers (a proxy of
 welfare in a sense).
 Given the nature of status competitions in society, such a calibration
 is hardly trivial.
 A study by Heffetz
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "heffetz_visibility"

\end_inset

 using this model involved surveying a few hundreds of respondents asking
 them - quite literally - just how visible every item is for a typical consumer
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Heffetz considers the visibility of items and conducts a visibility survey
 to find that the degree to which people notice items explains the corresponding
 (permanent) income elasticities better.
 This observation has provided the basis for inspection of visible consumption
 in many studies thereforth.
 In an environment of inequalities, however, it is likely that the individuals
 with perceived higher status notice items differently from how the lower
 status individuals might notice them.
 The social factors thus also become relevant for the difference in visible
 preferences in the developing countries.
 In India, these are religion and caste (lower casters may spend more on
 visible items) - while in South Africa and United States, race seems to
 have a dominant significance (blacks, hispanics spend more on visible items).
 The research on conspicuous consumption in the developing world has often
 found that the consumption of visible items (for a certain selected criterion)
 differs significantly between social classes 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kaus finds that black ethnic groups spend more on visible commodities than
 the white ethnic population in South Africa - arguing that status is gained
 through means other than consumption
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"

\end_inset

.
 Khamis et al find that the Muslims spend less on visible consumption items
 when compared to Hindus of same economic standing
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Further, the developing countries may offer a less consumerist agrarian
 environment overall where expenditure is more visible than in a relatively
 individualistic and industrialized society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
That measuring visibility may require some judgment is demonstrated by the
 varied criteria of visibility baskets.
 In an environment of severe inequalities and scarcities in the developing
 countries, visibility as a criterion for conspicuous consumption must be
 enhanced with an association with higher income.
 Khamis et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

 therefore perform a slightly more detailed survey by asking what an individual
 whose consumption is noticed would do when her income rises (by 20%).
 This quantifies the expectations from others associates the total expenditure
 with higher-income.
 The items where consumers expect the consumption to rise with increased
 income are those that associate with higher income and are declared 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conspicuous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the study.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Visible goods are neither clear-cut nor so relevant in the developing markets
 where products are less uniform, a culture of mass consumerism is only
 nascent and status competitions aren't driven by income inequalities alone
 (whereas in developed markets, firms are quick to turn a conspicuous item
 into a higher-priced commodity).
 The context of exploits identified by Veblen is however still relevant
 in the developing markets
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

No class of society, not even the most abjectly poor, forgoes all customary
 conspicuous consumption
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In its original sense, conspicuous consumption is a social-cultural mechanism
 and is driven by the particular context of the society.
 The demand for status goods as well as what is considered a status good
 may change as society responds to its newer circumstances
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Veblen had stressed upon social confirmation as the motivation for newer
 consumption patterns at the time.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Increased mobility of the members has also added to the facility with which
 a “social confirmation” can be attained within the class.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Conspicuous consumption in developing economies encompasses more than just
 noticeability (visibility).
 While visible consumption may detail the mechanics of status competitions
 in a narrow sense where consumers participate in a market to increase their
 perceived status - but it does not provide an adequate picture of conspicuous
 consumption which is tied to of status.
 One reason for the inadequacy of visibility as a measure for status consumption
, is that the markets are underdeveloped in the developing world and social
 status is largely yielded through economic classes and social conditions.
 The second - probably more significant - reason is that status signaling
 does not exist in a society as an inherent need for visible appeal amongst
 humans.
 Instead visible consumption matters because of an item being associated
 with a higher status (at least in the sense which Veblen had talked about
 in his 19th century treatise
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both the developed and developing worlds, conspicuous consumption is
 driven by scarcity and competition (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits,FrankPond"

\end_inset

).
 If status were imparted by inherited wealth alone, there would be little
 conspicuous consumption as the consumers would be quick to realise the
 futility of buying trinkets.
 In the developed world, where markets have evolved to address the demands
 of the population, the positional pressures are readily addressed by market
 forces - thus a preference for visible goods indicates a higher price on
 them and a higher consumption on visible products always 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

signals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a higher status (a product with a higher status symbol would automatically
 carry a higher price).
 In underdeveloped markets, where information asymmetries are abound, the
 higher signalling (visible component of combined utility) would not necessarily
 be achieved with higher spending on visible goods - and factors such as
 social standing, asset ownership and educational level (which too are visible)
 start to matter in the combined utility function - as is suggested by data
 from various cross-section expenditure surveys.
 In Tanzania, for example, the spending on marriage and funerals seems high,
 but it now competes with higher spending on consumer electronics and electricit
y.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
A study of status and scarcity therefore goes hand in hand in study of conspicuo
us consumption.
 Instead of limiting ourselves to visible consumption as the particular
 mechanics of status signaling - where consumers buy items in a common market
 and (presumably) over-weigh on items that are more noticeable - we attempt
 to understand the reasons behind status-signaling by looking at the differences
 in patterns between the richer and poorer sections of society and to understand
 how unavailability of items (scarcity) as well as disparities of services
 across regions and classes in a society are reflected in both price and
 consumption of commodities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:StatusMap"

\end_inset

Measuring status appeal - Availability, Affordability and Popularity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The challenge to a theory for conspicuous consumption is the difference
 between what people can buy (with the available options for a given price
 and budget in the market locally) and what they wish to buy instead (options
 that could change the current consumption when they become available).
 While the income elasticity for every item in the consumption category
 indicates how the consumption changes with response to increase in income
 or prices, the degree to which consumption on existing items would change
 by introduction of a new item or category (e.g.
 a new technology) is not explained by elasticities of demand of existing
 categories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
In analysis of a typical consumption survey, the substitution effect of
 the item explains whether consumers like an item more than the other while
 whether consumers buy more of the same item as they become richer and the
 price goes lower is captured by the income effect.
 While the analysis is typically based on the utility derived from products
 in the consumer basket, the research on conspicuous consumption has pointed
 out to relevance of visibility and scarcity of items in the utility function.
 To explore some such factors into the model for utility, the current study
 separates the price and budget concerns from the signaling appeal of the
 item.
 The conventional price and budget concerns are encompassed by 
\series bold
affordability
\series default
 of the item (which is simply a statement of price of the item).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Since the elasticities of products interpreted from the consumption data
 cannot measure how consumption might be transformed if new items were introduce
d, we introduce a parameter to measure the availability of the item.
 This is based on the observation that consumption on the same item varies
 between regions that have another item available vs places where the item
 is completely unavailable.
 In developing countries, the issue of availability is particularly relevant
 since rural areas are faced with unavailability of services and goods that
 are available (although limited) in the urban areas
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The unavailability can spiral into severe demand pressures through pressures
 on urban migration.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In the data from Tanzania, not only are region dummies significant in consumpti
on of items in the survey (particularly with respect to such as electricity
 which is completely unavailable in large parts of the country), but the
 availability of electricity seems to transform the income elasticities
 of demand for other expenditures as well (e.g.
 marriage).
 A model that we wish to develop for appeal of an item attempts to include
 this difference in availability between regions.
 This is why 
\series bold
availability
\series default
 is introduced as a concern different from affordability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other than price-budget concerns (affordability) and issues of supply (availabil
ity), status-signaling item can be tracked by its demand in the richer sections
 of the society.
 Higher popularity of the item (i.e.
 higher number of purchasers of the item in the population of consumers)
 can drive the appeal of the item down or up.
 Items like jewelry and luxury cars are those that cannot become extremely
 popular by definition.
 If such items were to become popular, then the richer consumers would rush
 to something else that indicates their higher status.
 Such items are known as snob items.
 Items which people rush to purchase - on the other hand - are called bandwagon
 items.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
It is worth emphasizing that in a market where product differentiation exists,
 items can change from snob type to bandwagon type (or vice versa) over
 time.
 It is important to have a dynamic model for bandwagon characteristics of
 an item.
 Items like new electronics are snob items when they're not affordable -
 but as they become more affordable with time they become bandwagon items.
 As consumers rush to them, they get replaced by a new snob item in the
 market.
  The effect of popularity of an item on to its demand can thus be in either
 direction i.e.
 limited supply would mean a higher appeal for snob items but high supply
 would mean less appeal.
 A time-series of expenditures can help us understand the trend in rushing
 towards certain items.
 The degree to which consumers rush to an item is termed as the bandwagon
 effect in the study
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
The snob or bandwagon effects must be seen in combination with affordability
 and availability.
 If the item is available and not affordable - then the price and budget
 constraints are more important than the bandwagon characteristics of the
 item.
 The snob or bandwagon nature of the item matters for an individual consumer
 only when it is affordable (thus potentially popular) as well as available.
 This is in accordance with the discussion in Section
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ScarcityClarification"

\end_inset

 i.e.
 all direct physical scarcities are perceived scarcities.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
In summary, the appeal of a certain commodity can be estimated by its availabili
ty, affordability and popularity in the model.
 Availability encompasses all issues that put an item in the market.
 Regional and supply-side issues thus affect availability.
 In absence of the data on supply of the items, we assign availability as
 a binary variable which is set to true in a region when the item appears
 in the consumption data for the region.
 Affordability, on the other hand, sums up price-related concerns on the
 demand-side.
 An item is affordable solely based on the price of the average consumption
 unit.
 Further, the popularity of an item is measured as percentile of users of
 item i.e.
 the percentile which consumes the quantity.
 Popularity of an item may increase or decrease the consumption of an item
 based on whether the item is a snob or bandwagon type.
 An individual is likely to lose interest in a particular jewelry product
 if it the latter is available and affordable to everybody.
 In the Hirschian terminology
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"

\end_inset

, a physical scarcity is only realized by the availability of an item while
 social scarcities are realised through affordability and popularity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Measuring Availability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
In the absence of supply data, availability is simply a binary variable
 - indicating whether an item is either available or not in the local consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Measuring Affordability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
For every individual an item is more affordable if its cost is within the
 threshold percentage of the (permanent) income.
 If consumers spend a high portion of their income on rice than on vegetables,
 then using the simple price criterion, rice is less affordable than vegetables.
 One reason for choosing a method based on total cost spent on the item
 is the unavailability of quantities of consumption in the diary recall
 section - where only total costs of the item have been collected (rather
 than prices or quantities).
 Semantically, affordability is a statement of price in the market and should
 be calculated from the average price of the item.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
For example, to answer whether AC is more affordable than electricity (the
 two are compared only to stress that any two commodities can be compared
 based on the criterion), we use just average cost of AC in the population
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 consumers (i.e.
 for item 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 amongst total  number of items the average price is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N}\Sigma_{n=1}^{N}(\frac{q_{i}}{\Sigma^{K}q_{k}})$
\end_inset

 ).
 If average expenditure on AC amongst those who buy AC (i.e.
 the cost of AC) is higher than than the respective mean for electricity,
 then AC would be considered less affordable than electricity.
 That electricity is a service and consumed immediately (as opposed to AC
 which is an asset) is currently ignored in the model.
 The dependency amongst items is also ignored in the model.
 (i.e.
 that one cannot consume A.C.
 without consuming electricity is ignored).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
We also note that prices can be significantly different between regions.
 As discussed there are categories for which difference prices may exists
 within the same region.
 The dummies 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

expensive_region
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are in fact statistically significant for some commodities.
 Following an approach similar to the one from Prais-Houthakker (see Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:PraisHouthakerPriceDiffferences"

\end_inset

), we could also interpret the affordability of expensive and cheap categories
 of the same item separately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measuring Reference Popularity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Appeal of items within the social-psychological communication is based on
 perceived differences between life standards and is thus relative to a
 reference area.
 At local levels this could be due to disparate neighborhoods while at national
 levels, reference areas could be metropolitan cities.
 The choice of reference area cannot be arbitrary - reference area is decided
 only between regions that are socially and economically inter-connected
 and thus where sufficient flow of information and people is possible.
 For the current analysis, Dar-es-salaam (region =7) is chosen as the reference
 area.
 The measure of popularity of an item is thus the reference area - i.e.
 the percentile of consumers using the product in the reference area.
 For example, only about 25% of the surveyed population uses electricity.
 Thus the popularity metric is set to .25 for electricity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The increase in appeal if the popularity in reference area were to increase
 (through increase in local availability) can be a proxy of the bandwagon
 effect of an item - i.e.
 a measure of how strongly an item's demand would increase as an items is
 more popular.
 If we denote the popularity of an item in the reference area by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ref}$
\end_inset

, then the measure of this effect is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial A}{\partial\rho_{ref}}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the change in appeal of the item in the reference area with respect to
 the change in the popularity of the item.
 Since appeal is represented by the demand of the item in the consumption
 survey, we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\gamma}{\partial\rho_{ref}}=\frac{\partial A}{\partial\rho_{ref}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\frac{q}{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the quantity purchased, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the total expenditure, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the appeal and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ref}$
\end_inset

 is the item's popularity in the reference area.
 If items have become more popular over time and if consumers are on average
 spending a higher portion of their income on the item, then the bandwagon
 effect of the item would be considered strong
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
Notice that the bandwagon effect 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is only calculated in the reference area.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above simple metrics can be used to calculate the model's prediction
 for the items which should have the most appeal.
 Table 
